von, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wythecombe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Widdicombe  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Widdicombe","meanings":["English (Devon): habitational name from Widdacombe in Thrushelton, Widdecombe in the Moor, Widdicombe in Marldon, Widdicome in Stokenham, Withycombe in Tedburn Saint Mary, or Withycombe Raleigh (all Devon), or from Withycombe (Somerset). Widdacombe in Thrushelton derives from Old English <i>wīd</i> ‘wide’ + <i>cumb</i> ‘valley’. Widdecombe in the Moor derives from Old English <i>wīd</i> or <i>wīthig</i> ‘withy, willow’ + <i>cumb</i>. The other placenames derive from Old English <i>wīthig</i> + <i>cumb</i>."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Wythecombe was born in 1382, in Whitcombe, Dorset, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 2 sons with Edith Mairsyn. He died in 1462, at the age of 80."},"et":{"1382–1462":"1382–1462","1385–1443":"1385–1443","1405–1462":"1405–1462","1412–Male":"1412–Surnud","1412":"1412","1443":"1443","1462":"1462","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","about 1443":"umbes 1443","1405":"1405","Whitcombe, Somerset, England":"Whitcombe, Dorset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Berwick Mavesyn, Shropshire, England":"Little Berwick, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England,":"Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"1382–1462":"1382–1462","1385–1443":"1385–1443